ChatGPT said:
Good â€” that error usually means one of these three things on .NET 9 + Avalonia.

Since you're using Avalonia UI, here is the correct way.

âœ… First: Make Sure You're Inside a Window or UserControl
DataContext exists on StyledElement (Window, UserControl, etc).

Your class must inherit from Window or UserControl:

using Avalonia.Controls;

namespace MyAvaloniaApp;

public partial class MainWindow : Window
{
    public string Message { get; set; } = "Hello";

    public MainWindow()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        DataContext = this; // âœ… This works
    }
}
If your class looks like this:

public partial class MainWindow
âŒ That will cause the error.

It must be:

public partial class MainWindow : Window
âœ… Second: Make Sure You Imported The Right Namespace
At the top:

using Avalonia.Controls;
Without that, Window wonâ€™t resolve correctly.

âœ… Third: Make Sure You're Not Inside a Static Context
This will fail:

public static class MainWindow
Because static classes donâ€™t have DataContext.

ğŸš€ Alternative (Cleaner Way â€” Recommended)
Instead of setting it in code, you can set it directly in XAML:

<Window
    xmlns:vm="using:MyAvaloniaApp"
    x:Class="MyAvaloniaApp.MainWindow">

    <Window.DataContext>
        <vm:MainWindow/>
    </Window.DataContext>

</Window>
âš  But this only works if MainWindow is NOT also the view.

Normally you'd create:

MainWindowViewModel.cs
Then:

<Window.DataContext>
    <vm:MainWindowViewModel/>
</Window.DataContext>
Thatâ€™s the proper MVVM structure.

