ChatGPT said:
Ah! Now weâ€™re seeing Avaloniaâ€™s compiled bindings error (AVLN2100).

This happens because Avalonia 11+ uses compiled bindings ({x:Bind} style) by default if the project targets C# source generators. Compiled bindings require you to explicitly tell the XAML what type the DataContext is using x:DataType.

You have two options:

Option 1 â€” Use â€œNormalâ€ Bindings (Simplest for now)
Replace compiled binding syntax (or just remove x:DataType) and use normal {Binding â€¦}.

<StackPanel HorizontalAlignment="Center"
            VerticalAlignment="Center"
            Spacing="10">

    <TextBlock Text="{Binding Incrementation}" FontSize="24" HorizontalAlignment="Center"/>
    <Button Content="Increase" Command="{Binding IncreaseCommand}"/>
</StackPanel>
Make sure you do not have x:DataType anywhere, and just use standard {Binding}.
âœ… This works without AVLN2100.

Option 2 â€” Use Compiled Bindings Properly
If you want the performance and safety of compiled bindings, you must tell XAML the type of the DataContext:

At the top of your Window:

<Window
    xmlns="https://github.com/avaloniaui"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
    xmlns:vm="using:test1"
    x:Class="test1.MainWindow"
    x:DataType="vm:MainWindowViewModel">
Then bindings become:

<TextBlock Text="{Binding Incrementation}"/>
<Button Content="Increase" Command="{Binding IncreaseCommand}"/>
Notes:

vm:MainWindowViewModel matches the namespace/class of your ViewModel.

This solves AVLN2100 because Avalonia now knows the type of DataContext at compile time.

You cannot use {Binding} or {x:Bind} without either setting DataContext in code or using x:DataType.

âœ… Summary
Approach	Pros	Cons
Normal {Binding}	Simple, beginner-friendly	Slightly slower, no compile-time checking
Compiled {Binding} with x:DataType	Fast, compile-time safety	Slightly more setup required
My Recommendation
Since youâ€™re just starting:

Use normal {Binding} for now (remove x:DataType entirely).

Later, when confident with MVVM, switch to compiled bindings with x:DataType.

